{{liushu|p}} — [[moon]] [[crescent]]. Compare to its ancient variant {{zh-l|*月}}.

===Etymology 1===
Related to {{och-l|汐|evening tide}}.

{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} suggests it is from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*rV-jak||day; full day; to spend the night}}; cognate with {{cog|bo|ཞག||day (24 hours)}}, {{cog|lus|riak||to pass the night}}, {{cog|kac||tr=jaʔ⁵⁵|t=day (24 hours)}}, {{cog|my|ရက်||day (24 hours)}}, {{cog|lhu|há||night; to pass the night}}; may also be cognate with {{och-l|宿|to spend the night}} and {{och-l|昔|former times}}. It is noted that in the oracle bone script, the 24 hour day started and ended some time in the evening or night. Since {{zh-l|日|sun}} has acquired the meaning of "day (24 hours)", {{lang|zh|夕}} was then restricted to the time of the day's end.

On the other hand, STEDT suggests {{och-l|夕|evening; night}} was derived from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*ja-n||night}}, from which {{och-l|夜|night}} was also derived. However, {{lang|zh|夕}} was also compared to {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*rV-jak||day; full day; to spend the night}}. {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} assigns Chinese {{m|zh|夜}} to {{l|sit-pro|*ja|gloss=night}} instead, and notes {{l|sit-pro|*ja|gloss=night}} and {{l|sit-pro|*ryak|gloss=day (24 hours)}} were kept strictly separate in Tibeto-Burman.

